 SeisBench Model\n# ==========================================\n# EQTransformer is highly recommended for robust picking in noisy environments\nmodel = sbm.EQTransformer.from_pretrained(\"original\")\n\n# ==========================================\n# 4. Generate Phase Picks\n# ==========================================\n# The pick() method processes the stream and returns a list of pick dictionaries\npicks = model.pick(stream)\n\n# ==========================================\n# 5. Format and Export Picks\n# ==========================================\nif picks:\n    df_picks = pd.DataFrame(picks)\n    \n    # Display the picks\n    print(f\"Found {len(df_picks)} phase picks:\")\n    print(df_picks[['trace_id', 'phase', 'peak_time', 'start_time', 'end_time']])\n    \n    # Save to CSV\n    df_picks.to_csv(\"seismic_picks.csv\", index=False)\n    print(\"\\nPicks successfully saved to seismic_picks.csv\")\nelse:\n    print(\"No seismic phases detected in the provided waveforms.\")\n```\n\n### 3. Bonus: Formatting Picks for GaMMA Associator\nIf your downstream goal is to associate these picks into earthquake events using the **GaMMA algorithm** (as outlined in the `gamma-phase-associator` skill guide), GaMMA expects a specific CSV format containing station coordinates. \n\nYou can append this block to the script above to convert the SeisBench output into the GaMMA-compatible format:\n\n```python\n# Assume you have a dictionary of station metadata (lat, lon, elev)\nstation_metadata = {\n    \"STA1\": {\"lat\": 34.05, \"lon\": -118.25, \"elev\": 0.1},\n    # Add other stations...\n}\n\ngamma_picks = []\nfor p in picks:\n    # trace_id is typically formatted as \"NET.STA.LOC.CHA\"\n    net, sta, loc, cha = p['trace_id'].split('.')\n    \n    # Extract station coordinates\n    coords = station_metadata.get(sta, {\"lat\": 0.0, \"lon\": 0.0, \"elev\": 0.0})\n    \n    gamma_picks.append({\n        \"fname\": p['trace_id'],       # GaMMA uses this to group traces\n        \"phases\": p['phase'],         # 'P' or 'S'\n        \"timestamp\": p['peak_time'],  # UTC datetime of the pick\n        \"station\": sta,               # Station name\n        \"lat\": coords[\"lat\"],\n        \"lon\": coords[\"lon\"],\n        \"elev\": coords[\"elev\"]\n    })\n\n# Save in GaMMA expected format\ndf_gamma = pd.DataFrame(gamma_picks)\ndf_gamma.to_csv(\"gamma_picks.csv\", index=False)\nprint(\"Picks formatted and saved for GaMMA association.\")\n```\n\n### Key Considerations:\n* **Model Selection:** While `PhaseNet` is another excellent SeisBench model strictly for picking, `EQTransformer` is generally preferred when you also need simultaneous event detection (the \"Noise\" probability curve helps filter out false picks from cultural noise).\n* **Sampling Rate:** SeisBench models are strictly trained on specific sampling rates (100 Hz for EQTransformer/PhaseNet). Failing to resample your mseed data will result in silently shifted pick times or errors.\n* **Trace IDs:** SeisBench relies on the `trace.id` (e.g., `NET.STA.LOC.CHA`) to map picks back to specific stations. Ensure your mseed headers are correctly populated with SEED standard codes before picking.", "solver_finish_reason": "stop"}
