oupId>\n            <artifactId>bad-transitive-artifact</artifactId>\n        </exclusion>\n    </exclusions>\n</dependency>\n```\n\n### 3. Fix Compilation Errors (Java Version Mismatch)\nIf you see `invalid target release` or `source option X is no longer supported`:\n\nEnsure your `pom.xml` explicitly defines the Java compiler source and target versions matching your installed JDK:\n```xml\n<properties>\n    <maven.compiler.source>17</maven.compiler.source>\n    <maven.compiler.target>17</maven.compiler.target>\n    <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>\n</properties>\n```\n*Verify your environment is using the correct JDK:*\n```bash\nmvn -version\n```\nIf it points to the wrong JDK, set your `JAVA_HOME` environment variable to the correct JDK path before running Maven.\n\n### 4. Fix \"Corrupted Artifact\" or \"Checksum Invalid\" Errors\nIf Maven fails to download a dependency or complains about a corrupted JAR in your local cache:\n\n**Purge and re-download local repository artifacts for the project:**\n```bash\nmvn dependency:purge-local-repository\n```\n\n**Or, manually nuke the local cache for the specific failing artifact:**\n```bash\n# Linux/macOS\nrm -rf ~/.m2/repository/com/failing/group/artifact/\n\n# Windows\nrmdir /s /q %USERPROFILE%\\.m2\\repository\\com\\failing\\group\\artifact\\\n```\nThen rebuild:\n```bash\nmvn clean install -U\n```\n*(The `-U` flag forces Maven to check for updated releases and snapshots on remote repositories).*\n\n### 5. Fix Plugin Execution Failures\nIf a specific plugin (e.g., `maven-surefire-plugin`, `maven-compiler-plugin`) fails:\n\n**Skip tests temporarily to isolate the issue:**\n```bash\nmvn clean install -DskipTests\n```\n\n**Update the plugin version in `pom.xml`:**\n```xml\n<build>\n    <plugins>\n        <plugin>\n            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>\n            <artifactId>maven-surefire-plugin</artifactId>\n            <version>3.2.5</version> <!-- Update to latest stable -->\n        </plugin>\n    </plugins>\n</build>\n```\n\n### 6. Fix \"Out of Memory\" (OOM) or \"Metaspace\" Errors during Build\nIf the build crashes with `java.lang.OutOfMemoryError`:\n\nIncrease the memory allocated to the Maven JVM by setting the `MAVEN_OPTS` environment variable before running the build:\n```bash\n# Linux/macOS\nexport MAVEN_OPTS=\"-Xmx2048m -XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=512m\"\n\n# Windows\nset MAVEN_OPTS=-Xmx2048m -XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=512m\n```\nThen run your build command again.\n\n### 7. Nuclear Option: Full Clean and Rebuild\nIf the local state is completely broken and nothing else works, clear the `target` directories and force a full update:\n```bash\nmvn clean\nrm -rf target/\nmvn clean install -U -X\n```", "solver_finish_reason": "stop"}
{"task": "fix-druid-loophole-cve", "condition": "no_skill", "repeat": 0, "skill_ids": [], "retrieval_correct": null, "judged_pass": false, "judged_score": 1, "judge_reason": "The proposed solution does not match the oracle's approach of creating a git patch for CVE-2021-25646 by modifying SamplerResource.java and rebuilding specific JARs.", "solver_tokens": 2955, "judge_tokens": 1714, "solution_text": "To address an Apache Druid security CVE via a Maven build, you have two primary approaches depending on whether you are consuming Apache Druid as a dependency in your own project, or building Apache Druid itself from source. \n\nBelow is the complete, actionable solution for both scenarios.\n\n### Approach 1: Upgrade to the Official Patched Release (Recommended)\nIf you are building Apache Druid from source or using it as a dependency, the safest and most complete way to patch CVEs (such as CVE-2023-25194, CVE-2023-38205, etc.) is to upgrade to the official Apache Druid release where the vulnerability was patched.\n\n**1. Update your `pom.xml` to the latest secure version:**\n```xml\n<dependency>\n    <groupId>org.apache.druid</groupId>\n    <artifactId>druid-indexing-service</artifactId>\n    <!-- Update to the latest patched version, e.g., 28.0.0 or newer -->\n    <version>28.0.0</version> \n</dependency>\n```\n\n**2. Rebuild your project:**\n```bash\nmvn clean install -DskipTests\n```\n\n---\n\n### Approach 2: Patch Transitive Dependencies in an Existing Build\nIf you are locked to a specific older version of Apache Druid but need to patch a known vulnerable transitive dependency (e.g., `jackson-databind`, `log4j-core`, or `commons-text`) exposed by Druid, you can force the secure version using Maven's `<dependencyManagement>` block.\n\n**1. Identify the vulnerable dependency:**\nRun the OWASP Dependency Check plugin to find the exact CVE and artifact:\n```bash\nmvn org.owasp:dependency-check-maven:check -DfailBuildOnCVSS=7\n```\n*(Check the generated `target/depen